# Vue Reactivity Project Feedback
**Student:** Joanna Zhang

This is a pizza topping builder — the core reactive functionality works well with a proper `ref`, `v-for`, and `@click` handler, though there are some incomplete pieces and no BEM CSS.

## Vite CLI – Mastery
`package.json` correctly includes `vite` and `vue` with proper scripts set up.

## Iteration in Vue – Mastery
`v-for` is used with `:key` bound to a unique value on the topping elements. Correct pattern.

## Data Binding – Mastery
`selectedToppings` is declared as `ref([])` and bound in the template. Data is displayed correctly with `{{ }}`. `v-model` is used for input fields.

## Click Methods – Mastery
`addToPizza()` is defined and connected with `@click="addToPizza(topping)"`. The function correctly uses `.value` to push to the ref array. This is working correctly.

## Reactive UI – Mastery
Adding a topping updates the selected toppings list immediately in the template. The reactive system is working as intended.

## Semantic HTML – Approaching
The topping list uses a good structure. Consider wrapping the displayed selected toppings in a `<ul>/<li>` structure if they are currently in plain `<div>` elements:

```html
<ul>
  <li v-for="topping in selectedToppings" :key="topping.name">
    {{ topping.name }}
  </li>
</ul>
```

## BEM CSS – Not Yet
No BEM class names are used. Class names like `card`, `list`, `button` are generic. Apply BEM naming convention:
- `pizza-builder` (block)
- `pizza-builder__topping` (element)
- `pizza-builder__topping--selected` (modifier)

## Bonus – Aesthetics – Approaching
The layout is clean and functional. The `totalprice.vue` component appears to be empty — completing it and adding a running total display would add a lot to the user experience.

## Summary of Critical Fixes
- **Complete `totalprice.vue`** — it's an empty file. Add logic to calculate and display the total price of selected toppings.
- **Add BEM class names** to your CSS following `block__element--modifier` convention.
- **Wrap selected toppings in `<ul>/<li>`** if they are currently in `<div>` elements.
- Fix any import ordering issues — in JavaScript/ES modules, imports should be at the top of the file.